feed.title: Samsung Note 8 rumours: dual camera, 4K curved display
feed.introtext:
There are several things that Samsung skipped on the Galaxy S8 which are said to make appearance on the next Note flagship. Let's begin with one of the oldest rumour. Like Apple saves some of the best stuff for its bigger screen variant, Samsung does it for the note flagship. It introduced an iris scanner on the Note 7 and then brought it to Galaxy S8. The Note 8 is said to come with a dual camera setup in the rear

The inner hardware of the phone is not known, but many say it is Exynos 8895 for Asian markets and Snapdragon 835 for the US. Expect 6GB RAM and 128 GB storage variant with audio enhancements, new S-Pen features, and probably a battery monitoring app. Also, Note 8 will be running the same software as the Galaxy S8. But yes, it will come with a stylus and the abilities to crop your way around apps as well as take notes on the go.

feed.title: Inside a phone factory: How smartphones are made
feed.introtext:
Many smartphone companies of the world are manufacturing their smartphone models in India. This video takes you inside one such factory. The assembly line readies over 10,000 smartphones in a day, and the process includes comprehensive tests that take around as much time as that of assembling the phone.

Contrary to what you may think, the major part of the manufacturing process is carried out manually. Smartphone components like the camera, chipset, speakers and batteries are shipped separately and assembled by the factory staff. The video also shows the testing processt that is done after the phones are assembled and booted for the first time.

feed.title: Xiaomi Mi Note 3: dual camera and other expected features
feed.introtext:
Succeeding Mi Note 2, Xiaomi's top end flagship with dual curve edge display is the upcoming Mi Note 3. The phone has leaked several times in the past and is said to come with a set of dual cameras at the back. In terms of specifications, the upcoming Xiaomi Mi Note 3 will feature a 5.7-inch QHD curved AMOLED display from Samsung, with 2560 x 1440 pixels resolution.

It is said to house the latest Snapdragon 835 chipset, similar to the OnePlus 5, with 6GB and 8GB RAM variants. Xiaomi Mi Note 3 which is expected to launch next month will run on MIUI 9. This is all the new report reveals about the device.

feed.title: Nokia 3310 (2017): Unboxing the India variant
feed.introtext:
Nokia has launched its much-awaited feature phone of 2017 in India. The phone will be available only on offline retail stores for now at Rs 3310. The phone, which has 2.5 inch display and physical keys is the touted as Nokia's best product after comeback, at least as far as the nostalgia is concerned.

Nokia 3310 isn't a 4G phone and doesn't connect with Wi-Fi. Neither does it run essential apps like WhatsApp or Uber. But it does give a battery backup of a month on standby or a talk time of 22h. Combine both and you have almost a fortnight of backup, vis-Ã -vis a single day on your smartphone. Holds good while you are trekking in jungles

feed.title: iPhone 8, OnePlus 5 and other phones to launch with dual cameras
feed.introtext:
Dual cameras are clearly the next trend in smartphone industry. While several phones have used them on before and it is nothing new, but almost every phone in the coming months and years will probably have a dual camera setup at its back. For now, we list some popular phones that are expected to come with dual camera setups. For now, most of them are flagships. But expect the trend to trickle down to budget phones soon.

Dual rear camera is not just a good looking gimmick but a useful feature. It is more versatile than a single camera as you can switch for a wider field of view or zoom in without compromising on the quality. Companies are upping the ante by adding background blur and selective focus features. Apple and Motorola are infact expect to bring depth sensing and Augmented reality features on their iPhone 8 and Moto X4

feed.title: Smartron's Sachin phone vs Xiaomi Redmi Note 4
feed.introtext:
Smartron's latest Srt.phone backed by cricket legend Sachin Tendulkar has been one of the series budget contenders launched by an Indian company in the recent times. While there are few misses, it is a bold attempt by Smartron, the Srt.phone being its second device. But how does it stack up against the budget king from Xiaomi -- the Redmi Note 4?

The comparison clears several things about both the smartphone. Like we know srt.phone's camera is a bummer, but how bad is it? Or how fast the Redmi Note 4 could be if it had a stock interface with the latest Android 7.0 Nougat? The srt.phone comes in a polycarbonate unibody with no micro SD card support but the Redmi Note 4 has a metal unibody design and a hybrid slot to expand storage.

feed.title: MP3 is officially dead and its time to rejoice
feed.introtext:
Internet's favourite music format, that is the MP3 is proclaimed dead. Actually, the people who created it back in the 90s, the Fraunhofer Institute for Integrated Circuits, have ended support for the same with the termination of its licensing hold after 22 years. The codec has become obsolete as more efficient ones have taken its place, feels the institute.

But this means the licensing fee MP3 player manufacturers need to pay to Fraunhofer IIC will no longer be required, making them cheaper. And offcourse, you can still use the audio format. On the other hand, adoption of a more efficient codec, like the AAC, will happen at a wider scale, improving the out of box music experience of phones, PCs and other gadgets.

feed.title: Google I/O 2017: AI for cancer detection, Android O and other key announcements
feed.introtext:
Google held its annual I/O conference for 2017 on May 17 in Mountain View, the US city where Google has its main office. The I/O has always been a conference for developers and consequently is not event where the big bang, most exciting announcements are made by Google. Android Go is arguably the most important announcement Google made at the I/O 2017 as far as its Indian users are concerned. The lighter version of the OS will work well even with less costly hardware.

Google is also working with hardware partners - Qualcomm, HTC and Lenovo - to make VR headsets that will be similar to Facebook's Oculus and HTC's own Vive. The company showcased how it is focusing on the improving user experience in Android O through features like Vitals and Fluid Experience and that the beta version of it will be available as OTA. To get it manually, read here; http://indiatoday.intoday.in/technology/story/android-o-beta-top-features-how-to-get-it-and-everything-to-know/1/956708.html.

Google is going to use the machine learning, artificial intelligence and Google Assistant to offer users some cool features, which seem to be straight out of a futuristic movie, including advancements in medical field with more accurate detection of diseases like Cancer.
